02","1235":"1235","1286":"1286","1250":"1250","1270":"1270","Traean Glas, Breconshire, Wales":"Traeanglas, Breconshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Traeanglas, Breconshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Traeanglas, Breconshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Wales":"Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"ap","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Dutch: from a short form of the personal name <i>Adelhard</i>, which is of ancient Germanic origin, composed of the elements <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>hard</i> ‘bold, hardy’. Compare   Ale   and   Alma   4.","Swedish: variant of   Ahl  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ale","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Carlos Enrique, Cesar, Jose, Maria De Jesus.","Spanish (Andalusia; <b>Alé</b>): unexplained.","Italian (Sicily; <b>Alé</b>): probably a variant of   Aleo  ."]}]},{"name":"Hywel","type":"LAST","meanings":["A Welsh name. Some write the name Hoel, which they render 'lordly;' if so, it may come from huail, a vice-regent, regent. Arthur derives the surname Howell from Corn. -Brit, houl, the sun; and he adds, high, exalted.' But Hywel is rather from hywel, conspicuous."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Gwilym","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of <b>William</b> , in use since the Middle Ages."],"variants":[{"name":"Gwilim","meanings":["equivalent of <b>William</b> , in use since the Middle Ages."]},{"name":"Gwillym","meanings":["equivalent of <b>William</b> , in use since the Middle Ages."]},{"name":"William","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Gwilym ap Hywel was born in 1270, in Wales, his father, Hywel ap Gwgon, was 36 and his mother, Mrs. Hywel Ap Gwyon, was 32. He had at least 2 sons with Margaret Elin Howel."},"et":{"1270–":"1270–Surnud","1270–Male":"1270–Surnud","1250–Female":"1250–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1286–Male":"1286–Surnud","1302–Male":"1302–Surnud","1235–Male":"1235–Surnud","1239–Female":"1239–Surnud","1239":"1239","1302":"1302","1235":"1235","1286":"1286","1250":"1250","1270":"1270","Traean Glas, Breconshire, Wales":"Traeanglas, Breconshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Traeanglas, Breconshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Traeanglas, Breconshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Wales":"Wales"},"fi":{"1270–":"1270–Kuollut","1270–Male":"1270–Kuollut","1250–Female":"1250–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1286–Male":"1286–Kuollut","1302–Male":"1302–Kuollut","1235–Male":"1235–Kuollut","1239–Female":"1239–Kuollut","1239":"1239","1302":"1302","1235":"1235","1286":"1286","1250":"1250","1270":"1270","Traean Glas, Breconshire, Wales":"Traeanglas, Breconshire, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Traeanglas, Breconshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Traeanglas, Breconshire, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Wales":"Wales"},"fr":{"1270–":"1270–Décédé","1270–Male":"1270–Décédé","1250–Female":"1250–Décédée","–Female":"Décédée","1286–Male":"1286–Décédé","1302–Male":"1302–Décédé","1235–Male":"1235–Décédé","1239–Female":"1239–Décédée","1239":"1239","1302":"1302","1235":"1235","1286":"1286","1250":"1250","1270":"1270","Traean Glas, Breconshire, Wales":"Traeanglas, Breconshire, Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni","Traeanglas, Breconshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Traeanglas, Breconshire, Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni","Wales":"Galles","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Gwilym ap Hywel est né